04995nam a2200685Ia 9789815104424DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898151044247 a10.1355/97898151044242doi  a(DE-B1597)690344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0290002bisacsh00aPutting Women Up :bGender Equality and Politics in Myanmar /ced. by Netina Tan, Meredith L Weiss. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (220 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tLIST OF TABLES -- tLIST OF FIGURES -- tACRONYMS AND GLOSSARY -- tAcknowledgements -- tABOUT THE CONTRIBUTORS -- t1 Putting Women Up: Promoting Gender Equality in Myanmar Politics -- t2 The Secret Garden of Candidate Selection and Women’s Political Participation -- t3 Ethnic Parties, Representation, and Female Candidate Recruitment in Myanmar -- t4 Attitudes Towards Women and Political Leadership -- t5 Violence, Gender, and Politics -- t6 Navigating Local Politics and Gender -- tAppendices -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the duration of Myanmar’s experiment with electoral democracy, why did some women run for political office, and not others? What role did gatekeepers such as party leaders play in those decisions, and using what criteria in selecting candidates? How did experience of domestic violence or harassment affect women’s likelihood to participate in politics, especially beyond the local level? And what implications might these earlier patterns have for a post-coup Myanmar, should meaningful elections be restored? The contributors to Putting Women Up: Gender Equality and Politics in Myanmar answer these questions by examining the internal politics of nine political parties in Myanmar and both men’s and women’s attitudes towards and experiences of political leadership. Drawing on extensive interview, survey, and focus-group discussion data collected from across Myanmar in 2017 and 2020, this book offers a mixed-methods approach to explain how factors from party rules to formative personal trauma to patriarchal biases to ethno-religious context shape women’s and men’s likelihood to join local and national politics. The findings expand on culturalist insights on gender inequality to provide context-sensitive, evidence-backed policy recommendations to promote women’s political leadership, despite militarization and violence in post-coup Myanmar.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aWomenxPolitical activityzBurma. 4aPolitical Ideologies - Democracy. 4aSocial Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aBjarnegård, Elin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDion, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJap, Jangai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinoletti, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMu, Anor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPausa, La Ring, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreece, Cassandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRiambau, Guillem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTan, Netina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTan, Netina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTun, Aye Lei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss, Meredith L, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeiss, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r